<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 39. Choosing the Pattern and Calculating Adjustments by Software.</h1>
<p><strong>Let us imagine a real-life situation. A woman has brought a sketch of a dress asking if you can sew it for her. </strong>You fill out the order form and she signs it in confirmation. This means no more changes to the style: you will choose a certain pattern and start cutting and sewing a certain garment.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image045.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>Before taking measurements, you examine the client attentively for a rough estimation of her size.</p>
<p><strong>At this point, you must already have a clear understanding of what basic corset pattern you will work with and what pattern you will use for the top. </strong></p>
<p><strong>You must also specify </strong>whether your clients wants a corset with a lace overlay (see above), a smooth surface corset with an imitation of a lace top underneath, or a separately sewn top for wearing over the corset. It is also very important because it affects your work strategy.</p>
<p><strong>Suppose you can tell that your client is a slender girl with a small bust size. You can now start taking measurements. </strong></p>
<p><strong>There is already a certain plan on your mind! </strong>You have decided that it is best to use a boat-neck corset pattern with four front princess seams for cutting a corset like this for a small girl. It is easy to turn a boat neck into a sweetheart neck by rounding the corners.</p>
<p><strong>It is important to draw the neckline shape correctly and determine its depth at this stage. </strong>If your client was prepared for taking measurements and put on a slim-fit top, then you can take a disappearing ink pen and draw a graceful neckline right on it. If her clothes are not suitable for that, then you can use an elastic band to design the neckline. It will be much easier for you to take related measurements correctly after you decide on neckline shape and depth.</p>
<p><strong>It is clear from the picture that the top worn over the corset has cap-sleeves. </strong>Sample cap-sleeves will really help in this case: you will put them on the client and determine the best sleeve length for her.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>You also need to choose a suitable pattern for the top. In this particular case, it is my pattern of a corset with shoulders. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I recommend you should not pay attention to the princess seam lines which you can see on the sketch or picture brought by the client. </strong>No one will ever start comparing the number of princess seams on the picture and on the finished garment.</p>
<p><strong>The most important thing is a good fit! </strong>And your client does not care how you will achieve it.</p>
<p>In the rare case when your client is very picky, you can always adjust the standard pattern accordingly and transfer all princess seams, darts, and other modelling lines onto it.</p>
<p><strong>So you have agreed on the style and it is time to take all measurements off the client. </strong>Apart from the key measurements, you need certain addition measurements for this particular garment.</p>
<p><strong>For example, you will need all supplementary measurements taken for a corset with shoulders.</strong> Remember about Bust to Shoulder, Bust to Shoulder Tip, Shoulder, Sleeve Length, and Armscye Circumference. Make sure to measure your client’s Arm Fullness (it is the area where the cap-sleeve ends which will help you determine its width correctly). Other compulsory measurements are Centre Length Back, Waist to Shoulder Blade, and two Side Seam Length measurements (one for the corset and another for the top). Make sure to take Clip toward Neckline correctly with regard to the desired neckline shape. Do not forget to measure Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front and Across Back, Nape to Waist, Shoulder Slope Back, and Full Length Back. Measure Neck Depth, i.e. how far above or below the bust line the lowest neckline point is positioned. There is one more additional measurement which I sometimes use: Centre Waist to Sternal Notch Front. It helps calculate Neck-Hole Depth correctly for the top.</p>
<p><strong>All measurements have been taken.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us first work on the corset itself.</strong></p>
<p><strong>As we already know, we will use the basic boat-neck corset pattern with four front princess seams. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We will use the Automatic Pattern Adjustments Calculator to customize it to our client’s size. </strong></p>
<p><strong>It is crucial to choose the right table.</strong> In our particular case, it is the Table for Automatic Calculation of Adjustments to the Pattern with Four Front Princess Seams.</p>
<p><strong>Here is what it looks like initially: </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>It is very easy to use these tables. </strong>All you need to do is put your client’s measurements in the corresponding boxes. And if your mock-up measurements differ from the suggested pattern measurements, you can change them as well. That’s it, all calculations are done! All values in blue boxes are the values you need to adjust the standard pattern.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image050.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I have drawn the initial pattern on the writing board. </strong>As for you, you should print it out and make all adjustments on paper. It is also a good idea to print out the table with calculated values to keep it before your eyes.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image051.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I look at the table and start applying adjustments to the standard pattern.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image052.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The first adjustment concerns the centre of the front. </strong>It is clear from the table that I need to remove 1cm along the fold line of the centre front piece.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image053.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us look at the next column: Princess Seam Side Front (One Edge).</strong> It is the princess seam line of the intermediate front piece.</p>
<p>You can probably remember it from my tutorials on the anatomy of corset patterns that the intermediate front piece has a cup with a dart on it and part of this dart is compensated for in this princess seam to ensure the right fit.</p>
<p>The additional princess seam at the side of the front gives you more opportunities of adjusting the pattern with regard to your client’s individual body features.</p>
<p><strong>According to the table, this princess seam line must be shifted 1.5cm inwards so as to narrow the intermediate front piece along its full length. </strong></p>
<p><strong>This means the entire intermediate front piece is narrowed by the same value – 1.5cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image054.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the next column: Side Seam Front. </strong></p>
<p>The front side seam line must be shifted 2cm outwards to compensate for the narrowed centre piece and intermediate piece.</p>
<p><strong>In other words, I widen the initial side front piece by 2cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>And the back side seam line remains unchanged. There are zeroes in the table. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image055.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Almost all adjustments have been applied to the front of the corset</strong> but I still cannot say for sure whether it became smaller or bigger. I guess the volume got re-distributed between the pieces because of our client’s bust size and clip measurement.</p>
<p><strong>Let us look at the clip measurement then. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The table shows that Clip toward Armscye must be shortened by 1.5cm.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image056.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>At the same time, we need to preserve the length of the princess seam. </strong>By shifting the princess seam line inwards to narrow the piece, we reach the required clip measurement shortened by 1.5cm.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image057.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Top of Cup is made 3.3cm shorter in accordance with the calculations.</strong></p>
<p><strong>By re-drawing this clip, I automatically shorten the overall cup length and the bust princess seam. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image058.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Finally, I mark a 6cm Clip toward Middle of Neckline from the bust point of the centre front piece. Do not forget about a 1.2cm seam allowance, too. &nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image059.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I draw a graceful neckline and simultaneously even out the lengths of bust princess seams.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image060.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The corner needs to be rounded according to the chosen neckline style. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image061.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I move to the princess seams.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us first apply adjustments to the princess seams at the front and then to those at the back.</strong></p>
<p>I shift <strong>the princess seam line of the centre front piece</strong> 0.3cm inwards at the waist level and 0.4cm outwards at the stomach level and connect the new points with a smooth graceful line.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image062.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Then I move to the bust princess seam line of the intermediate front piece. </strong>I am supposed to shift it 0.3cm inwards at the waist level and 0.4cm outwards at the stomach level. My experience, however, tells me that 0.4cm added at the stomach level will distort the princess seam line very badly. <strong>So I simply gradually bring the new princess seam line down to point zero. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image063.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I will compensate for the remaining 0.4cm by shifting outwards the princess seam line of the side front piece at the stomach level. </strong>This will not affect the configuration of the princess seam line.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image064.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I encourage you to take the same creative approach when applying adjustments to patterns. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Before we move to the back princess seams, let me adjust the side length. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I need to add 0.5cm to the Side Seam Length and shorten the Back Length by 0.8cm. </strong></p>
<p>I recommend you should draw the new side seam line using the initial pattern as a template.</p>
<p>In this case, you will preserve the original length of the side seam.</p>
<p>And then you will see based on your calculations whether you need to adjust the length or not.</p>
<p>Needless to say, all notches must also be transferred onto the new lines.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image065.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Now we can look at the back princess seams. </strong></p>
<p><strong>According to my calculations, I shift it 0.5cm inwards at the bust line level, 0.3cm outwards at the under-bust level, 0.3cm inwards at the waist level, and 0.4cm outwards at the stomach level. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the back princess seam lines accordingly. </strong></p>
<p>Do not be scared off by these somewhat angled back princess seam lines.</p>
<p>The princess seams will look perfectly smooth after you press them.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image066.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>All changes have been applied. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image067.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>All you need to do afterwards is double-check everything to make sure the adjustments correspond with the calculated values and the princess seam edges have matching lengths.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Then you can cut out the adjusted pattern and prepare fabric for cutting.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2039.files/image068.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>As for us now, we still need to calculate adjustments to the lace top pattern. </strong></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
</div> <!-- Scope END: Article -->
<!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin -->
 
					</div>

					
					
					<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">
						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p>
<p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p>
<p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p>
<a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> 
